7) What does the umask value of 0022 indicates for a root user? \par
\par
 ANSWER:Before understanding this, one must understand the numerical values being used to represent permission bits in Unix environment. It is as shown below:\par
\par
      r - "read" permission - numerical equivalent value "4"\par
      w - "write" permission - numerical equivalent value "2"\par
      x - "execute" permission - numerical equivalent value "1"\par
      s - "special" permission bit - numerical equivalent "4" for SUID (SetUserID), "2" for SGID(SetGroupID "1" for Sticky-bit.\par
   \par
      u - "user"  \par
      g - "group" \par
      o - "others"       \par
     \par
      Set/Unset Permissions: Using chmod command. Say for example you wish to set only "read & write (rw)" permission for owner, no permissions for group and others then this could be done like below:\par
     \par
      $chmod 600 <filename> OR $chmod u+rw,go-rwx <filename>\par
     \par
     \par
Now, lets check what does 0022 umask value indicates:\par
   \par
      0 - Indicates special character bit, not masked.\par
      0 - Indicates mask nothing, all permission bits are set for "Owner".\par
      2 - Indicates mask 2 for "Group" (for files it is "x4x" meaning both read & write bits are set likewise for directories it is "x5x" meaning both read & execute bits are set)\par
      2 - Indicates mask 2 for others ( as explained above)\par
     \par
               Saying so, when a root user creates a file/directory this umask bit would be used to set the effective permissions. For a file it would be (666-022=644), rw-,r--,r-- (read&write,read,read) respectively for user, group and others (ugo). However, when a directory is created it would be (777-022=755) rwx,r-x,r-x for ugo. Same way the default umask value for other users is 0002.\par
